    {"instruction": "What is the cheapest competitive Legacy deck?", "input": "", "output": "Oops All Spells at approximately $1100 is the cheapest tier 1 Legacy deck. It runs zero dual lands, and its most expensive cards are Force of Will and some sideboard staples. Burn at approximately $1500 is another budget option that avoids dual lands entirely. Belcher at approximately $1200 is similarly affordable. All three decks can win tournaments despite their low cost."},
    {"instruction": "Can I play competitive Legacy on a budget?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, several competitive decks cost under $2000. Oops All Spells ($1100), Burn ($1500), Belcher ($1200), and Dredge ($2000 with LED) are all tournament-viable. Red Stompy ($2500-3000 without Fiery Confluence) avoids dual lands. Eldrazi ($2100) uses only colorless lands. The key is choosing a deck whose expensive cards are staples you will use forever, and avoiding Reserved List cards you cannot afford."},
    {"instruction": "What is the cheapest way to build Dimir Tempo?", "input": "", "output": "The minimum viable Dimir Tempo build replaces Underground Sea with Watery Grave and cuts some expensive sideboard cards. This brings the cost from $5000 down to approximately $1500-2000. The 2-life-per-use cost from Watery Grave reduces your win rate by a few percentage points against aggressive decks but is functional against combo and control. Force of Will ($80-100 each) is the single biggest non-land expense and is not replaceable."},
    {"instruction": "How do I build a budget mana base for a two-color Legacy deck?", "input": "", "output": "Replace dual lands with the corresponding shock land (Watery Grave for Underground Sea, etc.). Run 3-4 basics to protect against Wasteland. Keep all fetchlands since they are $20-40 each and essential for Brainstorm. Consider running 1-2 slow fetches (Flood Plain for UW decks) to save on expensive Zendikar fetches. Total mana base cost drops from $2000-3000 to $200-400 with this approach."},

    # === TRADE-OFF ANALYSIS ===
    {"instruction": "How much worse is a shock land than a dual land in Legacy?", "input": "", "output": "In practice, replacing all dual lands with shock lands reduces your win rate by approximately 3-5%. The 2 life per untapped use costs you 4-10 life per game from lands alone, which is critical against Burn (where every point matters), Ocelot Pride (fast aggro), and Dimir Tempo (which can Bolt or Bowmasters you for remaining life). Against combo decks that do not care about your life total, the difference is negligible. The biggest risk is against Price of Progress, which deals double damage for each nonbasic land you control."},
    {"instruction": "Is it worth buying dual lands for Legacy?", "input": "", "output": "Dual lands are on the Reserved List and can never be reprinted, so they hold or increase in value over time. If you plan to play Legacy long-term, buying duals is both a gameplay investment and a financial one. Start with 2-3 copies of your primary dual and upgrade over time. Many players begin with shock lands and buy one dual at a time. The difference in gameplay quality is real but not insurmountable."},
    {"instruction": "What Reserved List cards are essential vs optional in Legacy?", "input": "", "output": "Essential: Dual lands are needed for competitive multicolor decks and have no close substitutes. Optional: Lion's Eye Diamond (only in Storm and Dredge), Mox Diamond (only in Lands and some Stompy decks), City of Traitors (Ancient Tomb is a non-Reserved alternative for most decks), Gaea's Cradle (only in Elves and Cradle Control). The Tabernacle at Pendrell Vale is only in Lands and costs more than some cars. Focus your Reserved List budget on dual lands first."},
    {"instruction": "What are the best budget-friendly sideboard cards?", "input": "", "output": "Many powerful Legacy sideboard cards are very affordable. Pyroblast and Hydroblast ($1-3 each), Surgical Extraction ($5-8), Mindbreak Trap ($5), Flusterstorm ($10-15), Deafening Silence ($1), Null Rod ($15-20), and Grafdigger's Cage ($2) are all cheap and highly effective. Leyline of the Void ($5-10) is the most played sideboard card in the format and costs almost nothing. Expensive sideboard cards like Endurance ($30-40) and Force of Vigor ($15-20) have budget alternatives."},
